  { :title => "Example 12", :description => "Here we start with white one piece behind.  The goal of white is to use the threat of what we saw in Example 11 to force black into losing an additional piece...and (as we will see) it is a very important piece", :start => "f8-black-♜,g8-black-♚,b7-black-♝,c7-black-♛,e7-black-♝,f7-black-♟,h7-black-♟,a6-black-♟,c6-black-♞,g6-black-♟,b5-black-♟,d4-white-♞,b3-white-♟,d3-white-♟,e3-white-♜,h3-white-♛,a2-white-♟,b2-white-♝,c2-white-♟,g2-white-♟,h2-white-♟,h1-white-♚", :lesson_id => 16, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-07-23 03:44:41", :next_exercise => "31", :sort_for_lesson => 2, :conclusion => "The example illustrates the danger of advancing the g-pawn one square after castling on that side: a well placed ♝ can be used to protect a penetrating ♜ or ♛" },
  { :title => "Example 13", :description => "Another interesting combination. Black has a ♜ over white's ♞ and should therefore win.  White's focus is to immediately compensate.  It is however white that has the upper hand and mates in only a few moves", :start => "c8-black-♛,f8-black-♜,g8-black-♚,b7-black-♝,f7-black-♟,g7-black-♟,h7-black-♟,a6-black-♟,b6-black-♟,c5-black-♟,c4-white-♟,e4-white-♞,a3-white-♟,b3-white-♟,d3-white-♛,b2-white-♝,f2-white-♟,g2-white-♟,h2-white-♟,g1-white-♚", :lesson_id => 16, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-08-21 01:58:24", :next_exercise => "32", :sort_for_lesson => 3, :conclusion => "White starts with a disadvantage, but is able to capitalize on positioning by drawing out and disrupting the ♟ barrier that ends up becoming a trap for black" },
  { :title => "Example 14", :description => "This is another similar formation,  however more complex: white is at a disadvantage -- they have a ♝ where black has a ♜", :start => "c8-black-♛,e8-black-♜,f8-black-♜,g8-black-♚,b7-black-♝,c7-black-♟,d7-black-♞,f7-black-♟,g7-black-♟,h7-black-♟,a6-black-♟,b6-black-♟,d6-black-♟,b5-white-♝,e4-white-♞,b3-white-♟,d3-white-♛,e3-white-♜,a2-white-♟,b2-white-♝,c2-white-♟,f2-white-♟,g2-white-♟,h2-white-♟,g1-white-♚", :lesson_id => 16, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-07-23 04:26:02", :next_exercise => "33", :sort_for_lesson => 4, :conclusion => "Again we see how positioning and pinning of the ♚ can be used to establish mate" },
  { :title => "Example 15", :description => "A very frequent type of combination is shown in the following position.  White uses sacrifice to exploit the black's castle and trap the ♚", :start => "a8-black-♜,e8-black-♛,f8-black-♜,g8-black-♚,b7-black-♟,c7-black-♟,f7-black-♟,g7-black-♟,h7-black-♟,a6-black-♟,c6-black-♞,d6-black-♟,d5-white-♛,a3-white-♟,d3-white-♝,f3-white-♞,b2-white-♟,c2-white-♟,f2-white-♟,g2-white-♟,h2-white-♟,d1-white-♜,g1-white-♚", :lesson_id => 16, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-07-23 04:44:06", :next_exercise => "34", :sort_for_lesson => 5, :conclusion => "Again we see how black's castling can be used to trap their ♚ and exploit what is left" },
  { :title => "Example 16", :description => "This same type of combination is seen in a more complicated form in the following position.", :start => "c8-black-♞,d8-black-♝,f8-black-♜,g8-black-♚,b7-black-♟,c7-black-♛,d7-black-♜,e7-black-♞,f7-black-♟,g7-black-♟,h7-black-♟,a6-black-♟,d6-black-♟,c5-black-♟,d5-white-♛,f5-white-♞,g4-white-♟,b3-white-♟,d3-white-♝,f3-white-♞,h3-white-♟,a2-white-♟,e2-white-♜,f2-white-♟,d1-white-♜,g1-white-♚", :lesson_id => 16, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-07-24 22:22:56", :next_exercise => "undefined", :sort_for_lesson => 6, :conclusion => "This combination is rather long and has many variations; therefore a beginner will hardly be able to fathom it; but knowing the type of combination; he might under similar circumstances undertake and carry out a brilliant attack which he would otherwise never think of. It will be seen that all the combinations shown have for a foundation the proper co-ordination of the pieces; which have all been brought to bear against a weak point." },
  { :title => "Example 17", :description => "Suppose we begin:", :start => "a8-black-♜,b8-black-♞,c8-black-♝,d8-black-♛,e8-black-♚,f8-black-♝,g8-black-♞,h8-black-♜,a7-black-♟,b7-black-♟,c7-black-♟,d7-black-♟,e7-black-♟,f7-black-♟,g7-black-♟,h7-black-♟,a2-white-♟,b2-white-♟,c2-white-♟,d2-white-♟,e2-white-♟,f2-white-♟,g2-white-♟,h2-white-♟,a1-white-♜,b1-white-♞,c1-white-♝,d1-white-♛,e1-white-♚,f1-white-♝,g1-white-♞,h1-white-♜", :lesson_id => 18, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-08-22 20:30:27", :next_exercise => "36", :sort_for_lesson => 1, :conclusion => "A very powerful move; which brings us to the middle-game stage; as there is already in view a combination to win quickly by _ - _ 5. This threat makes it impossible for Black to continue the same course. (There is a long analysis showing that Black should lose if he also plays _ - _ 5.) He is now forced to play 7..._ x _; as experience has shown; thus bringing up to notice three things. First; the complete development of the opening has taken only seven moves. (This varies up to ten or twelve moves in some very exceptional cases. As a rule; eight should be enough.) Second; Black has  been compelled to exchange a Bishop for a Knight; but as a compensation he has isolated White's _ _ _ and doubled a Pawn. (This; at such an early stage of the game; is rather an advantage for White; as the Pawn is doubled towards the center of the board.) Third; White by the exchange brings up a Pawn to control the square _ 4; puts Black on the defensive; as experience will show; and thus keeps _the initiative_; an unquestionable advantage.[1] The strategically principles expounded above are the same for all the openings; only their tactical application varies according to the circumstances. Before proceeding further I wish to lay stress on the following point which the student should bear in mind. Before development has been completed no piece should be moved more than once; unless it is essential in order to obtain either material advantage or to secure freedom of action._ The beginner would do well to remember this; as well as what has already been stated: viz.; _bring out the Knights before bringing out the Bishops_." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 18", :description => "N/A", :start => "a8-black-♜,b8-black-♞,c8-black-♝,d8-black-♛,e8-black-♚,f8-black-♝,g8-black-♞,h8-black-♜,a7-black-♟,b7-black-♟,c7-black-♟,d7-black-♟,e7-black-♟,f7-black-♟,g7-black-♟,h7-black-♟,a2-white-♟,b2-white-♟,c2-white-♟,d2-white-♟,e2-white-♟,f2-white-♟,g2-white-♟,h2-white-♟,a1-white-♜,b1-white-♞,c1-white-♝,d1-white-♛,e1-white-♚,f1-white-♝,g1-white-♞,h1-white-♜", :lesson_id => 20, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-08-23 02:34:10", :next_exercise => "37", :sort_for_lesson => 1, :conclusion => "With this last move White completes his development; while Black is evidently somewhat hampered. A simple examination will suffice to show that White's position  is unassailable. There are no weak spots in his armor; and his pieces are ready for any maneuver that he may wish to carry out in order to begin the attack on the enemy's position. The student should carefully study this example. It will show him that it is sometimes convenient to delay Castling. I have given the moves as they come to my mind without following any standard book on openings. Whether the moves given by me agree or not with the standard works; I do not know; but at the present stage of this book it is not convenient to enter into discussions of mere technicalities which the student will be able to understand when he has become more proficient." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 19.", :description => "N/A", :start => "a8-black-♜,b8-black-♞,c8-black-♝,d8-black-♛,e8-black-♚,f8-black-♝,g8-black-♞,h8-black-♜,a7-black-♟,b7-black-♟,c7-black-♟,d7-black-♟,e7-black-♟,f7-black-♟,g7-black-♟,h7-black-♟,a2-white-♟,b2-white-♟,c2-white-♟,d2-white-♟,e2-white-♟,f2-white-♟,g2-white-♟,h2-white-♟,a1-white-♜,b1-white-♞,c1-white-♝,d1-white-♛,e1-white-♚,f1-white-♝,g1-white-♞,h1-white-♜", :lesson_id => 20, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-08-23 03:06:50", :next_exercise => "undefined", :sort_for_lesson => 2, :conclusion => "Black; however; has no pieces out except his Queen; and White; with a Bishop and a Knight already developed; has a chance of obtaining an advantage quickly by playing _ - _ 5 anyway. The student is left to work out the many variations arising from this position.  These examples will show the practical application of the principles previously enunciated. The student is warned against playing Pawns in preference to pieces at the beginning of the game; especially _ - _ _ 3 and _ - _ _ 3; which are moves very commonly indulged in by beginners." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 20.", :description => "N/A", :start => nil, :lesson_id => 21, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-08-23 02:08:17", :next_exercise => "39", :sort_for_lesson => 1, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 21.", :description => "N/A", :start => nil, :lesson_id => 21, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-08-23 02:08:17", :next_exercise => "undefined", :sort_for_lesson => 2, :conclusion => "There are a good many other traps--in fact; there is a book written on traps on the chess board; but the type given above is the most common of all." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 22", :description => "The example given should be sufficient proof. We give a few moves of the main variation:--", :start => nil, :lesson_id => 22, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-08-23 02:08:27", :next_exercise => "undefined", :sort_for_lesson => 1, :conclusion => "This brings the game to a position which is won by Black; and which constitutes one of the classical endings of King and Pawns. I shall try to explain the guiding idea of it to those not familiar with it." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 23", :description => "In this position White's best line of defense consists in keeping his Pawn where it stands at R 2. As soon as the Pawn is advanced it becomes easier for Black to win. On the other hand; Black's plan to win (supposing that White does not advance his Pawn) may be divided into three parts. The first part will be to get his King to K R 6; at the same time keeping intact the position of his Pawns. (This is all important; since; in order to win the game; it is essential at the end that Black may be able to advance his rearmost Pawn one or two squares according to the position of the White King.)", :start => nil, :lesson_id => 23, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-08-23 02:09:16", :next_exercise => "undefined", :sort_for_lesson => 1, :conclusion => "It is in this analytical way that the student should try to learn. He will thus train his mind to follow a logical sequence in reasoning out any position. This example is excellent training; since it is easy to divide it into three stages and to explain the main point of each part. The next subject we shall study is the simple  opposition; but before we devote our time to it I wish to call attention to two things." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 24", :description => "In the above position the way of obtaining a passed Pawn is to advance the center Pawn.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "undefined", :sort_for_lesson => 65, :conclusion => "and the game properly played would be a draw. The student should work this out for himself." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 25", :description => "In this position whoever moves first wins.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "42", :sort_for_lesson => 64, :conclusion => "The student would do well to acquaint himself with various simple endings of this sort; so as to acquire the habit of counting; and thus be able to know with ease when he can or cannot get there first. Once again I must call attention to the fact that a book cannot by itself teach how to play. It can only serve as a guide; and the rest must be learned basally experience; and if a teacher can be had at the same time; so much the faster will the student be able to learn." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 26", :description => "Suppose in the above position White plays", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "43", :sort_for_lesson => 63, :conclusion => "The opposition can take the form shown above;  which can be called actual or close frontal opposition; or this form: which can be called actual or close diagonal opposition; or; again; this form: which can be called actual or close lateral opposition. In practice they are all one and the same. The Kings are always on squares of the same color; there is only one intervening square between the Kings; and the player who has moved last \"_has the opposition_.\" Now; if the student will take the trouble of moving each King backwards as in a game in the same frontal; diagonal or lateral line respectively shown in the diagrams; we shall have what may be called _distant_ frontal; diagonal and lateral opposition respectively. The matter of the opposition is highly important; and takes at times somewhat complicated forms; all of which can be solved mathematically; but; for the present; the student should only consider the most simple forms. (An examination of some of the examples of King and Pawns endings already given will show several cases of close opposition.) In all simple forms of opposition; when the Kings are on the same line and the number of intervening squares between them is even; the player who has the move has the opposition_." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 27", :description => "The above position shows to advantage the enormous value of the opposition. The  position is very simple. Very little is left on the board; and the position; to a beginner; probably looks absolutely even. It is not the case; however. _Whoever has the move wins._ Notice that the Kings are directly in front of one another; and that the number of intervening squares is _even_.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "44", :sort_for_lesson => 62, :conclusion => "Now by counting it will be seen that White wins by capturing Black's Knight Pawn." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 27a", :description => "N/A", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "45", :sort_for_lesson => 61, :conclusion => "which brings the position back to the first variation shown. The student would do well to familiarize himself with the handling of the King in all examples of opposition. It often means the winning or losing of a game." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 28", :description => "The following position is an excellent proof of the value of the opposition as a means of defense.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "46", :sort_for_lesson => 60, :conclusion => "attacking the Pawn and forcing Black to play 6... _ - _ 6 when he can go back to _ 3 as already shown; and always keep the opposition." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 28a", :description => "N/A", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "47", :sort_for_lesson => 59, :conclusion => "and mere counting will show that both sides Queen; drawing the game. If the student will now take the trouble to go back to the examples of King and Pawns which I have given in this book;[3] he will realize that in all of them the matter of the opposition is of paramount importance; as; in fact; it is in nearly all endings of King and Pawns; except in such cases where the Pawn-position in itself ensures the win." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 29", :description => "In the above position White cannot win; although the Black King is cornered; but in the following position; in which Black has a Pawn;", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "48", :sort_for_lesson => 58, :conclusion => "_White with the two Knights can only stalemate the King; unless Black has a Pawn which can be moved._" },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 30", :description => "Although he is a Bishop and a Pawn ahead the following position cannot be won by White.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "49", :sort_for_lesson => 57, :conclusion => "It is the greatest weakness of the Bishop; that when the Rook's Pawn Queens on a square of opposite color and the opposing King is in front of the Pawn; the Bishop is absolutely worthless. All that Black has to do is to keep moving his King close to the corner square." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 31", :description => "In the above position White with or without the move can win. Take the most difficult variation.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "50", :sort_for_lesson => 56, :conclusion => "It is generally thought by amateurs that the Knight is the more valuable piece of the two; the chief reason being that; unlike the Bishop; the Knight can command both Black and White squares. However; the fact is generally overlooked that the Knight; at any one time;  has the choice of one color only. It takes much longer to bring a Knight from one wing to the other. Also; as shown in the following Example; a Bishop can stalemate a Knight; a compliment which the Knight is unable to return." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 32.", :description => "The weaker the player the more terrible the Knight is to him; but as a player increases in strength the value of the Bishop becomes more evident to him; and of course there is; or should be; a corresponding decrease in his estimation of the value of the Knight as compared to the Bishop. In this respect; as in many others; the masters of to-day are far ahead of the masters of former generations. While not so long ago some of the very best amongst them; like Pillsbury and Tchigorin; preferred Knights to Bishops; there is hardly a master of to-day who would not completely agree with the statements made above.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "51", :sort_for_lesson => 55, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 33", :description => "This is about the only case when the Knight is more valuable than the Bishop.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "52", :sort_for_lesson => 54, :conclusion => "It is what is called a \"_block position_;\" and all the Pawns are on one side of the board. (If there were Pawns on both sides of the board there would be no advantage in having a Knight.) In such a position Black has excellent chances of winning. Of course; there is an extra source of weakness for White in having his Pawns on the same color-squares as his Bishop. This is a mistake often made by players. The proper way; generally; in an ending; is to have your Pawns on squares of opposite color to that of your own Bishop. When you have your Pawns on squares of the same color the action of your own Bishop is limited by them; and consequently the value of the Bishop is diminished; since the value of a piece can often be measured by the number of squares it commands. While on this subject; I shall also call attention to the  fact that it is generally preferable to keep your Pawns on squares of the same color as that of the opposing Bishop; particularly if they are passed Pawns supported by the King. The principles might be stated thus: When the opponent has a Bishop; keep your Pawns on squares of the same color as your opponent's Bishop._ Whenever you have a Bishop; whether the opponent has also one or not; keep your Pawns on squares of the opposite color to that of your own Bishop._ Naturally; these principles have sometimes to be modified to suit the exigencies of the position." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 34", :description => "In the following position the Pawns are on one side of the board; and there is no advantage in having either a Knight or a Bishop. The game should surely end in a draw.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "53", :sort_for_lesson => 53, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 35", :description => "Now let us add three Pawns on each side to the above position; so that there are Pawns on both sides of the board.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "54", :sort_for_lesson => 52, :conclusion => "It is now preferable to have the Bishop; though the position; if properly played out; should end in a draw. The advantage of having the Bishop lies as much in its ability to command; at long range; both sides of the board from a central position as in its ability to move quickly from one side of the board to the other." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 36", :description => "In the above position it is unquestionably an advantage to have the Bishop; because; although each player has the same number of Pawns; they are not balanced on each side of the board. Thus; on the King's side; White has three to two; while on the Queen's side it is Black that has three to two. Still; with proper play; the game should end in a draw; though White has somewhat better chances.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "55", :sort_for_lesson => 51, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 37", :description => "Here is a position in which to have the Bishop is a decided advantage; since not only are there Pawns on both sides of the board; but there is a passed Pawn (K R P for White; Q R P for Black). Black should have extreme difficulty in drawing this position; if he can do it at all.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "56", :sort_for_lesson => 50, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 38", :description => "Again Black would have great difficulty in drawing this position.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "57", :sort_for_lesson => 49, :conclusion => "The student should carefully consider these positions. I hope that the many examples will help him to understand; in their true value; the relative merits of the Knight and Bishop. As to the general method of procedure; a teacher; or practical experience; will be best. I might say generally; however; that the proper course in these endings; as in all similar endings; is: Advance of the King to the center of the board or towards the passed Pawns; or Pawns that are susceptible of being attacked; and rapid advance of the passed Pawn or Pawns as far as is consistent with their safety. To give a fixed line of play would be folly. Each ending is different; and requires different handling; according to what the adversary proposes to do. Calculation by visualizing the future positions is what will count." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 39", :description => "In this example we must mate either at Q R 1 or K R 8. The ending can be divided into two parts. Part one consists in driving the Black King to the last line. We might begin; as is generally done in all such cases; by advancing the King to the center of the board:", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "58", :sort_for_lesson => 48, :conclusion => "It will be seen that the ending is rather laborious. There are two outstanding features: the close following by the King; and the controlling of the squares of opposite color to the Bishop by the combined action of the Knight and King. The student would do well to exercise himself methodically in this ending; as it gives a very good idea of the actual power of the pieces; and it requires foresight in order to accomplish the  mate within the fifty moves which are granted by the rules." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 40", :description => "This is one of the standard positions which Black can often bring about. Now; it is White's move. If it were Black's move it would be simple; as he would have to move his Rook away from the King (find out why); and then the Rook would be  comparatively easy to win. We deduce from the above that the main object is to force the Black Rook away from the defending King; and that; in order to compel Black to do so; we must bring about the position in the diagram with _Black_ to move. Once we know what is required; the way to proceed becomes easier to find. Thus:", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "59", :sort_for_lesson => 47, :conclusion => "(The student should find out by himself how to win when 3...R - _ 8; 4 _ - _ 5 ch; _ - _ 2.)" },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 41", :description => "The procedure here is very similar. The things to bear in mind are that the Rook must be prevented from interposing at _ 1 because of an immediate mate; and in the same way the King must be prevented from going either to R 3 or B 1.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "60", :sort_for_lesson => 46, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 42", :description => "We shall now examine a more difficult position.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "61", :sort_for_lesson => 45, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 42a", :description => "N/A", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "62", :sort_for_lesson => 44, :conclusion => "Note; in these examples; that the checks at long range along the diagonals have often been the key to all the winning maneuvers. Also that the Queen and  King are often kept on different lines. The student should carefully go over these positions and consider all the possibilities not given in the text.  He should once more go through everything already written before proceeding further with the book." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 43", :description => "It is Black's move; and as he is a _ and P behind he must win quickly; if at all. He plays:", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "63", :sort_for_lesson => 43, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 44", :description => "Black's last move was P - K 6; played with the object of stopping what he thought was White's threat; viz.: R - Q R 5; to which he would have answered Q - B 5 ch and drawn the game by perpetual check. White; however; has a more forceful move; and he mates in three moves as follows:", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "64", :sort_for_lesson => 42, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 45", :description => "White has a beautiful position; but still he had better gain some material; if he can; before Black consolidates his defensive position. He therefore plays:", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "65", :sort_for_lesson => 41, :conclusion => "In these few examples the attacking has been done by Rooks and Bishops in combination with the Queen.  There have been no Knights to take part in the attack. We shall now give some examples in which the Knights play a prominent part as an attacking force." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 46", :description => "White is two Pawns behind. He must therefore press on his attack. The game continues:", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "66", :sort_for_lesson => 40, :conclusion => "Evidently an error which made the winning easier for White; as he simply took the Rook with the Knight and kept up the attack. Black should have played: 1 ... _ x _. Then would have followed: 2 _ - _ 6 ch; _ - _ 3; 3 _ x _; _ - _ 3; 4 _ - _ 5; _ - _ 2; 5 _ x _; _ - _ 2; 6 _ - _ 4; and Black should lose.[4]" },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 47", :description => "The student should carefully examine the position; as the sacrifice of the Bishop in similar situations is typical; and the chance for it is of frequent occurrence in actual play. The game continues:", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "67", :sort_for_lesson => 39, :conclusion => "White finally won.[5]" },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 48", :description => "Black is a Pawn behind; and there is no violent direct attack against White's King. Black's pieces; however; are very well placed and free to act; and by coordinating the action of all his pieces he is soon able not only to regain the Pawn but to obtain the better game. The student should carefully  consider this position and the subsequent moves. It is a very good example of proper co-ordination in the management of forces. The game continues:", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "68", :sort_for_lesson => 38, :conclusion => "Now Black will recover his Pawn." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 49", :description => "An examination of this position will show that Black's main weakness lies in the exposed position of his King; and in the fact that his Q R has not yet come into the game. Indeed; if it were Black's move; we might conclude that he would have the better game; on account of having three Pawns to two on the Queen's side; and his Bishop commanding the long diagonal.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "69", :sort_for_lesson => 37, :conclusion => "These positions have been given with the idea of acquainting the student with different types of combinations. I hope they will also help to develop his imagination; a very necessary quality in a good player. The student should note; in all these middle-game positions; that--_once the opportunity is offered; all the pieces are thrown into action \"en masse\" when necessary;_ and that _all the pieces smoothly co-ordinate their action with machine-like precision._ That; at least; is what the ideal middle-game play should be; if it is not so altogether in these examples." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 50", :description => "A good example of a successful direct attack against the King is shown in the following diagram:", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "70", :sort_for_lesson => 36, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 51", :description => "Another example of this kind:", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "71", :sort_for_lesson => 35, :conclusion => "The student should note that in the examples given the attack is carried out with every available piece;  and that often; as in some of the variations pointed out; it is the coming into action of the last available piece that finally overthrows the enemy. It demonstrates the principle already stated: _Direct and violent attacks against the King must be carried _en masse_; with full force; to ensure their success. The opposition must be overcome at all cost; the attack cannot be broken off; since in all such cases that means defeat._" },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 52", :description => "Played at the Havana International Masters Tournament; 1913. (French Defense.) White: J. R. Capablanca. Black: R. Blanco.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "72", :sort_for_lesson => 34, :conclusion => "These apparently simple games are often of the most difficult nature. _perfection in such cases is much more difficult to obtain than in those positions calling  for a brilliant direct attack against the King; involving sacrifices of pieces." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 53", :description => "From the Havana International Masters Tournament; 1913. (Ruy Lopez.) White: J. R. Capablanca. Black: D. Janowski.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "73", :sort_for_lesson => 33, :conclusion => "I have passed over the game lightly because of its difficult nature; and because we are at present concerned more with the opening and the middle-game than we are with the endings; which will be treated separately." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 54", :description => "Played at the Hastings Victory Tournament; 1919. (Four Knights.) White: W. Winter. Black: J. R. Capablanca.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "74", :sort_for_lesson => 32, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 55", :description => "Queen's Gambit Declined. (_The notes within brackets by Sir George Thomas._) White: Mr. F. F. L. Alexander. Black: Sir George Thomas.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "75", :sort_for_lesson => 31, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 56.", :description => "N/A", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "76", :sort_for_lesson => 30, :conclusion => "and Black won after a few moves." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 57", :description => "Another good example; in which is shown the advantage of the greater mobility of the pieces in an ending; is the following from a game Capablanca-Kupchick played at the Havana Masters Tournament; 1913. The full score and notes of the game can be found in the book of the tournament.  White's only advantage in the above position is that he possesses the open file and has the move; which will secure him the initiative. There is also the slight advantage of having his Pawns on the Queen's side united; while Black has an isolated _ _ _. The  proper course; as in the previous ending; is to bring the Rooks forward; so that at least one of them may be able to shift from one side of the board to the other; and thus keep Black's Rooks from moving freely. What this means in general theory has been stated already; it really means: _keep harassing the enemy; force him to use his big pieces to defend Pawns. If he has a weak point; try to make it weaker; or create another weakness somewhere else and his position will collapse sooner or later. If he has a weakness; and he can get rid of it; make sure that you create another weakness somewhere else_.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "77", :sort_for_lesson => 29, :conclusion => "This ending shows how easy it is to make weak moves; and how often; even in master-play; mistakes are made and opportunities are lost. It shows that; so long as there is no great advantage of material; even with a good position; a player; no matter how strong; cannot afford to relax his attention even for one move." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 58", :description => "A good proof of the previous statement is shown in the following ending between Marshall and Kupchick in one of their two games in the same Tournament (Havana; 1913).", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "78", :sort_for_lesson => 28, :conclusion => "The reason is evident. If 6...K - _ 3; 7 _ x _ ch;  _ x _; 8 _ x _; _ x _; 9 _ - _ 8 ch; _ - _ 3; 10 _ - _ 5 mate." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 59.", :description => "N/A", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "79", :sort_for_lesson => 27, :conclusion => "If there were nothing more in the ending it would not be of any great value; but there are other very interesting features. " },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 59a", :description => "Now suppose that after 1 _ - _ 6; _ - _ 3; 2 _ - _ 7; Black did not realize that _ - _ 1 was the only move to draw.  We would then have the following position:", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "80", :sort_for_lesson => 26, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 59c", :description => "Now; going back to the position shown on page 122; suppose that after 1 _ - _ 6; _ - _ 3; 2 _ - _ 7 ch; Black did not realize that _ - _ 5 was the only move to draw; and consequently played _ - _ 3 instead; we would then have the following position:", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "81", :sort_for_lesson => 25, :conclusion => "Now that we have explained the reasons why this position is won; we leave it to the student to work out the correct solution. The fact that out of one apparently simple ending we have been able to work out several most unusual and difficult endings should be sufficient to impress upon the student's mind the necessity of becoming well acquainted with all kinds of endings; and especially with endings of Rook and Pawns." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 60", :description => "From a game; Capablanca-Kreymborg; in the New York State Championship Tournament of 1910.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "82", :sort_for_lesson => 24, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 61", :description => "From the game Capablanca-Janowski; New York National Tournament of 1913.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "83", :sort_for_lesson => 23, :conclusion => "_Keep freedom of maneuver while hampering your opponent. There is one more thing of great importance; and that is that the winning side has always had a general strategically plan capable of being carried out with the means at his disposal; while often the losing side had no plan at all; but simply moved according to the needs of the moment." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 62", :description => "From the first game of the Lasker-Marshall Championship Match in 1907.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "84", :sort_for_lesson => 22, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 63", :description => "In the position of the diagram we have an exceedingly bad Pawn formation on Black's side. Black's Q B P is altogether backward; and White could by means of the open file concentrate  his forces against that weak point. There is also the square at White's Q B 5; which is controlled by White; and from where a White piece once established could not be dislodged. In order to get rid of it; Black would have to exchange it; which is not always an easy matter; and often when possible not at all convenient. The same holds true with regard to Black's K P; K B P and K _ P; which create what is called a \"hole\" at Black's K B 3. Such Pawn formations invariably lead to disaster; and consequently must be avoided.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "85", :sort_for_lesson => 21, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 64", :description => "In this position we might say that the White center Pawns have the attacking position; while the Black center Pawns have the defensive position. Such a formation of Pawn occurs in the French Defense. In such positions White most often attempts; by means of P - K B 4 and K B 5; to obtain a crushing attack against Black's King; which is generally Castled on the King's side. To prevent that;  and also to assume the initiative or obtain material advantage; Black makes a counter-demonstration by P - Q B 4; followed by P x P (when White defends the Pawn by P - Q B 3); and the concentrating of Black's pieces against the White Pawn at Q 4. This in substance might be said to be a determined attack against White's center in order to paralyze the direct attack of White against Black's King. It must be remembered that at the beginning of the book it was stated that _control of the center was an essential condition to a successful attack against the King_.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "86", :sort_for_lesson => 20, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 65.", :description => "N/A", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "87", :sort_for_lesson => 19, :conclusion => "Let us suppose the game went on; and that in some way White; by playing one of the Knights to _ 4 at the proper time; forced the exchange of both Knights; and then afterwards both the Bishops were exchanged; and we arrived at some such position as shown in the following diagram. (I obtained such a position in a very similar way once at Lodz in _Poland. I was playing the White pieces against a consulting team headed by Salwe.) Now we would have here the case of the backward _ _ _; which will in no way be able to advance to _ _ 4. Such a position may be said to be theoretically lost; and in practice a first-class master will invariably win it from Black. (If I may be excused the reference; I will say that I won the game above referred to.) After a few moves the position may be easily thus: The Black pieces can be said to be _fixed_. If White plays _ - _ _ 3; Black must answer _ - _ 2; otherwise he will lose a Pawn; and if White returns with the Queen to _ _ 3 Black will have again to return to _ _ 2 with the Queen or lose a Pawn. Thus Black can only move according to White's lead; and under such conditions White can easily advance with his Pawns to _ _ 4 and _ _ 4; until Black will be forced to stop _ - _ 5 by playing _ - _ _ 4; and we might finally have some such position as this:" },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 66.", :description => "N/A", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "88", :sort_for_lesson => 18, :conclusion => "Black would now be forced to play _ - _ 1; and White could then play _ - _ 2; and follow it up with _ _ 3; and thus force Black to play _ x _; which would give White a greater advantage. A careful examination of all these positions will reveal that; besides the advantage of freedom of maneuver on White's part; the power of the Pawn at _ 5 is enormous; and that it is the commanding position of this Pawn; and the fact that it is free to advance; once all the pieces are exchanged; that constitute the pivot of all White's maneuvers. I have purposely given positions without the moves which lead to them so that the student may become accustomed to build up in his own mind possible positions that may arise (out of any given situation). Thus he will learn to make strategically plans and be on his way to the master class. The student can derive enormous benefit by further practice of this kind." },
  { :title => "EXAMPLE 67", :description => "In order to further illustrate this point; I now give a game played in the Havana International Masters Tournament of 1913. (Queen's Gambit Declined.) White: D. Janowski. Black: A. Kupchick.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "89", :sort_for_lesson => 17, :conclusion => "The student should notice that; apart from other things; White throughout the game has had control of the Black squares; principally those at _ 5 and _ _ 5. From now on to the end of the book I shall give a collection of my games both lost and won; chosen so as to serve as illustrations of the general principles laid down in the foregoing pages." },
  { :title => "GAME 1", :description => "QUEEN'S GAMBIT DECLINED (Match; 1909) White: F. J. Marshall. Black: J. _. Capablanca.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "90", :sort_for_lesson => 16, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "GAME 10", :description => "PETROFF DEFENSE (St. Petersburg; 1914) White: J. R. Capablanca. Black: F. J. Marshall", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "91", :sort_for_lesson => 15, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "GAME 11", :description => "RUY LOPEZ (St. Petersburg; 1914) White: J. R. Capablanca. Black: D. Janowski.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "92", :sort_for_lesson => 14, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "GAME 12", :description => "FRENCH DEFENSE (New York; 1918) White: J. R. Capablanca. Black: O. Chajes.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "93", :sort_for_lesson => 13, :conclusion => "The interest of this game centers mainly on the opening and on the march of the White King during the final stage of the game. It is an instance of the King becoming a fighting piece; even while the Queens are still on the board." },
  { :title => "GAME 13", :description => "RUY LOPEZ (New York; 1918) White: J. S. Morrison. Black: J. R. Capablanca.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "94", :sort_for_lesson => 12, :conclusion => "A very lively game." },
  { :title => "GAME 14", :description => "QUEEN'S GAMBIT DECLINED (New York; 1918) White: F. J. Marshall. Black: J. R. Capablanca.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "95", :sort_for_lesson => 11, :conclusion => "An ending worth very careful study." },
  { :title => "GAME 2", :description => "QUEEN'S GAMBIT DECLINED (San Sebastian; 1911) White: A. K. Rubinstein. Black: J. R. Capablanca.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "96", :sort_for_lesson => 10, :conclusion => "As an end game; this is rather a sad exhibition for two masters. The redeeming feature of the game is _Rubinstein's fine combination in the middle game; beginning with 14 _ x _." },
  { :title => "GAME 3", :description => "IRREGULAR DEFENSE (Havana; 1913) White: D. Janowski. Black: J. R. Capablanca.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "97", :sort_for_lesson => 9, :conclusion => "The game went on for a few more moves; and; there being no way to counteract the advance of White's two passed Pawns; Black resigned." },
  { :title => "GAME 4", :description => "FRENCH DEFENSE (St. Petersburg; 1913)", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "98", :sort_for_lesson => 8, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "GAME 5", :description => "RUY LOPEZ (St. Petersburg; 1914) White: Dr. E. Lasker. Black: J. R. Capablanca. ", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "99", :sort_for_lesson => 7, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "GAME 6", :description => "FRENCH DEFENSE (Rice Memorial Tournament; 1916) White: O. Chajes. Black: J. R. Capablanca.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "100", :sort_for_lesson => 6, :conclusion => "A very fine game on Chajes' part from move 25 on; for while Black; having the best of the position; missed several chances; White; on the other hand; missed none." },
  { :title => "GAME 7", :description => "RUY LOPEZ (San Sebastian; 1911) White: J. R. Capablanca. Black: A. Burn", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "101", :sort_for_lesson => 5, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "GAME 8", :description => "CENTRE GAME (Berlin 1913) White: J. Mieses. Black: J. R. Capablanca.", :start => nil, :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "102", :sort_for_lesson => 4, :conclusion => nil },
  { :title => "GAME 9", :description => "QUEEN'S GAMBIT DECLINED (Berlin; 1913) White: J. R. Capablanca. Black: R. Teichmann.", :start => "a8-black-♜,b8-black-♞,c8-black-♝,d8-black-♛,e8-black-♚,f8-black-♝,g8-black-♞,h8-black-♜,a7-black-♟,b7-black-♟,c7-black-♟,d7-black-♟,e7-black-♟,f7-black-♟,g7-black-♟,h7-black-♟,a2-white-♟,b2-white-♟,c2-white-♟,d2-white-♟,e2-white-♟,f2-white-♟,g2-white-♟,h2-white-♟,a1-white-♜,b1-white-♞,c1-white-♝,d1-white-♛,e1-white-♚,f1-white-♝,g1-white-♞,h1-white-♜", :lesson_id => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 15:33:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:47:47", :next_exercise => "103", :sort_for_lesson => 3, :conclusion => "The student ought to have realized by this time the enormous importance of playing well every kind of ending. In this game again; practically from the opening; White aimed at nothing but the isolation of Black's _ _. Once he obtained that; he tried for and obtained; fortunately; another advantage of position elsewhere which translated itself into the material advantage of a Pawn. Then by accurate playing in the ending he gradually forced home his advantage. This ending has the merit of having been played against one of the finest players in the world." }
])



Lesson.create!([
  { :title => "Power of Pieces", :description => "This lesson highlights the power of the the Major (non-Pawn) pieces by showing situational Mates.  The goal is to show the maximum amount of damage that can be done with the minimum of pieces on the board and fewest moves to be made.  Typically one or two of a certain piece type are shown as white plus the white King against only the black King.", :created_at => "2013-04-15 20:17:48", :updated_at => "2013-09-18 16:39:04" },
  { :title => "Power of Pawns", :description => "This lesson highlights how Pawns can be used in concert or alone to force promotion (reach the opponents final rank).  Additionally, it highlights forced Stalemate in one situation.", :created_at => "2013-04-15 21:06:01", :updated_at => "2013-08-30 15:14:26" },
  { :title => "Tests", :description => "A lesson filled with test exercises", :created_at => "2013-05-28 19:23:43", :updated_at => "2013-05-28 19:23:43" },
  { :title => "Tests Too", :description => "Another lesson filled with test exercises", :created_at => "2013-06-16 02:46:39", :updated_at => "2013-06-16 02:46:55" },
  { :title => "Tests The Third!", :description => "A final lesson filled with test exercises", :created_at => "2013-06-16 02:46:58", :updated_at => "2013-06-16 02:47:29" },
  { :title => "Middle Games", :description => "By the time the student has digested all that has been previously explained they are, no doubt, anxious to get to the actual game and play with all the pieces.  However, before considering the openings we shall devote a little time to some combinations that often arise during the game, and which will give the reader some idea of the beauty of the game, once he becomes better acquainted with it.", :created_at => "2013-07-17 21:25:01", :updated_at => "2013-07-17 21:25:01" },
  { :title => "Piece Value", :description => "Before going on to the general principles of the openings, it is advisable to give the student an idea of the proper relative values of the pieces.  There is no complete and accurate table for all of them, and the only thing to do is to compare pieces separately.\r\nFor all general theoretical purposes the bishop and knight have to be considered as of the same value, though it is my opinion that the bishop will prove the more valuable piece in most cases - two bishops is always better than two knights.", :created_at => "2013-08-19 02:39:12", :updated_at => "2013-08-20 20:56:08" },
  { :title => "General Strategy of the Opening", :description => "The main goal in the openings of chess is to develop pieces as quickly as possible by getting them into play as fast as possible.  e4 or d4 are the most popular moves as they open up lanes for bishops and the queen.  No other first move(s) accomplish so much.", :created_at => "2013-08-20 20:56:12", :updated_at => "2013-08-20 21:07:33" },
  { :title => "Control of the Center", :description => "The four squares, K 4 and Q 4 on each side respec- \r\ntively, are the centre squares, and control of these \r\nsquares is called control of the centre. The control of \r\nthe centre is of great importance. No violent attack \r\ncan succeed without controlling at least two of these squares, and possibly three. Many a maneuver in \r\nthe opening has for its sole object the control of the \r\ncentre, which invariably ensures the initiative. It is \r\nweU always to bear this in mind, since it will often be \r\nthe reason of a series of moves which could not other- \r\nwise be properly understood. As this book progresses \r\nI shall dwell more fully on these different points. At \r\npresent I shall devote some time to openings taken \r\nat random and explain the moves according to general \r\nprinciples. The student will in that way train his \r\nmind in the proper direction, and will thus- have less \r\ntrouble in finding a way out when confronted with a \r\nnew and difficult situation. ", :created_at => "2013-08-22 20:34:11", :updated_at => "2013-08-23 01:54:40" },
  { :title => "Traps", :description => "I shall now give a few positions or traps to be avoided \r\nin the openings, and in which (practice has shown) \r\nbeginners are often caught. ", :created_at => "2013-08-23 01:56:54", :updated_at => "2013-08-23 01:58:00" },
  { :title => "A Cardinal Principle", :description => "In the position shown above, White can draw by \r\nplaying b4 according to the general rule that \r\ngoverns such cases, i.e. to advance the Pawn that is \r\nfree from opposition. But suppose that White, either \r\nbecause he does not know this principle or because he does not, in this case, sufficiently appreciate the value \r\nof its application; suppose, we say, that he plays \r\n1 a4. Then Black can win by playing 1...a5, applying one of the cardinal principles of \r\nthe high strategy of chess - a unit that holds two. \r\nIn this case one Pawn would hold two of the opponent's Pawns. The student cannot lay too much stress on this principle. It can be applied in many ways, and it constitutes one of the principal weapons \r\nin the hands of a master.", :created_at => "2013-08-23 01:59:02", :updated_at => "2013-08-23 02:07:56" },
  { :title => "A Classic Ending", :description => "", :created_at => "2013-08-23 02:08:46", :updated_at => "2013-08-23 02:09:06" }
])



