  { :piece_white => "♚", :starting_coordinate_white => "e1", :ending_coordinate_white => "g1", :explanation => nil, :exercise_id => 75, :move_number => 5, :computer => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 20:41:21", :updated_at => "2013-07-17 20:41:21", :piece_black => "♚", :starting_coordinate_black => "e8", :ending_coordinate_black => "g8" },
  { :piece_white => "♝", :starting_coordinate_white => "b5", :ending_coordinate_white => "c6", :explanation => nil, :exercise_id => 75, :move_number => 6, :computer => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 20:41:21", :updated_at => "2013-07-17 21:14:07", :piece_black => "...", :starting_coordinate_black => nil, :ending_coordinate_black => nil },
  { :piece_white => "...", :starting_coordinate_white => nil, :ending_coordinate_white => nil, :explanation => "Niemzowitch's variation, which I have played successfully in many a game. It gives White a very solid game. Niemzowitch's idea is that White will in due time be able to play ♟ - ♚ ♝ 4, opening a line for his Rooks, which, in combination with the posting of a Knight at ♚ ♝ 5, should be sufficient to win. He thinks that should Black attempt to stop the Knight from going to ♚ ♝ 5, he will have to weaken his game in some other way. Whether this is true or not remains to be proved, but in my opinion the move is perfectly good. On the other hand, there is no question that Black can easily develop his pieces. ♝ut it must be considered that in this variation White does not attempt to hinder Black's development, he simply attempts to build up a position which he considers impregnable and from which he can start an attack in due course.", :exercise_id => 75, :move_number => 7, :computer => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 20:41:21", :updated_at => "2013-07-17 20:41:21", :piece_black => "♟", :starting_coordinate_black => "d7", :ending_coordinate_black => "c6" },
  { :piece_white => "♟", :starting_coordinate_white => "d2", :ending_coordinate_white => "d3", :explanation => "The alternative, ♞ ♟ x ♝; gives White the best of the game, without doubt.[8]", :exercise_id => 75, :move_number => 8, :computer => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 20:41:21", :updated_at => "2013-07-17 20:41:21", :piece_black => "♝", :starting_coordinate_black => "b4", :ending_coordinate_black => "d6" },
  { :piece_white => "♝", :starting_coordinate_white => "c1", :ending_coordinate_white => "g5", :explanation => nil, :exercise_id => 75, :move_number => 9, :computer => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 20:41:21", :updated_at => "2013-07-17 21:14:07", :piece_black => "...", :starting_coordinate_black => nil, :ending_coordinate_black => nil },
  { :piece_white => "...", :starting_coordinate_white => nil, :ending_coordinate_white => nil, :explanation => "This move is not at all in accordance with the nature of this variation. The general strategical plan for White is to play ♟ - ♚ ♜ 3, to be followed in time by the advance of the ♚ ♞ ♟ to ♞ 4, and the bringing of the ♛ ♞ to ♚ ♝ 5 via ♚ 2 and ♚ ♞ 3 or ♛ 1 and ♚ 3. Then, if possible, the ♚ ♞ is linked with the other ♞ by placing it at either ♚ ♜ 4, ♚ ♞ 3, or ♚ 3 as the occasion demands. The White King sometimes remains at ♞ 1, and other times it is placed at ♚ ♞ 2, but mostly at ♚ ♜ 1. Finally, in most cases comes ♟ - ♚ ♝ 4, and then the real attack begins. Sometimes it is a direct assault against the King,[9] and at other times it comes simply to finessing for positional advantage in the end-game, after most of the pieces have been exchanged.[10]", :exercise_id => 75, :move_number => 10, :computer => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 20:41:21", :updated_at => "2013-07-17 20:41:21", :piece_black => "♟", :starting_coordinate_black => "h7", :ending_coordinate_black => "h6" },
  { :piece_white => "♝", :starting_coordinate_white => "g5", :ending_coordinate_white => "h4", :explanation => nil, :exercise_id => 75, :move_number => 11, :computer => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 20:41:21", :updated_at => "2013-07-17 20:41:21", :piece_black => "♟", :starting_coordinate_black => "c6", :ending_coordinate_black => "c5" },
  { :piece_white => "♞", :starting_coordinate_white => "c3", :ending_coordinate_white => "d5", :explanation => "To prevent ♟ - ♛ 4 and to draw White into playing ♞ - ♛ 5, which would prove fatal. Black's plan is to play ♟ - ♚ ♞ 4, as soon as the circumstances permit, in order to free his Queen and Knight from the pin by the Bishop.", :exercise_id => 75, :move_number => 12, :computer => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 20:41:21", :updated_at => "2013-07-17 21:14:07", :piece_black => "...", :starting_coordinate_black => nil, :ending_coordinate_black => nil },
  { :piece_white => "...", :starting_coordinate_white => nil, :ending_coordinate_white => nil, :explanation => "White falls into the trap. Only lack of experience can account for this move. White should have considered that a player of my experience and strength could never allow such a move if it were good.", :exercise_id => 75, :move_number => 13, :computer => nil, :created_at => "2013-07-17 20:41:21", :updated_at => "2013-07-17 20:41:21", :piece_black => "♟", :starting_coordinate_black => "g7", :ending_coordinate_black => "g5" },
